_**Big Mouth**_ is an American [adult](/wiki/Adult_animation "Adult
animation") [animated sitcom](/wiki/Animated_sitcom "Animated sitcom") created
by [Nick Kroll](/wiki/Nick_Kroll "Nick Kroll"), [Andrew
Goldberg](/wiki/Andrew_Goldberg_\(writer\) "Andrew Goldberg \(writer\)"),
[Mark Levin](/wiki/Mark_Levin_\(director\) "Mark Levin \(director\)"), and
[Jennifer Flackett](/wiki/Jennifer_Flackett "Jennifer Flackett") based on
Kroll and Goldberg's tweenage years growing up in the
[suburbs](/wiki/Westchester_County,_New_York "Westchester County, New York")
of [New York](/wiki/New_York_City "New York City"), with Kroll voicing his
fictional self.[1] The first season consisting of ten episodes premiered on
[Netflix](/wiki/Netflix "Netflix") on September 29, 2017.[2][3] On October 24,
2017, it was confirmed that a second season has been ordered to air in
2018.[4]

##
Summary[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Big_Mouth_\(TV_series\)&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: Summary")]

The series follows 7th grade best friends Nick Birch and Andrew Glouberman as
they navigate their way through puberty, masturbation, and sexual arousal.
Acting as sex-based [shoulder angels](/wiki/Shoulder_angel "Shoulder angel")
are the hormone monsters Maurice, who pesters Andrew and occasionally Nick and
Jay, and Connie, who pesters Jessi and occasionally Missy. Throughout the
series, the kids interact with people and objects who are personified in one
way or another and offer helpful, albeit confusing, advice in their puberty-
filled lives including the ghost of Duke Ellington, a French accented Statue
of Liberty, a pillow capable of getting pregnant, and even Jessi's own vagina.

##
Reception[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Big_Mouth_\(TV_series\)&action=edit&section=7
"Edit section: Reception")]

_Big Mouth_ has received critical acclaim since its official release. On
[Rotten Tomatoes](/wiki/Rotten_Tomatoes "Rotten Tomatoes"), the series has an
approval rating of 100% based on 16 reviews, with the critical consensus
reading, "_Big Mouth 's_ simplistic animation and scatalogical humor belie its
finely sketched characters and smart, empathetic approach to the messiness of
adolescence."[5] At [Metacritic](/wiki/Metacritic "Metacritic"), the show
currently holds a rating of 80 out of 100, based on 6 critics, indicating
"generally favorable reviews".[6]

[Vox](/wiki/Vox_\(website\) "Vox \(website\)") described the show as sharp,
and as jarringly depicting the awkwardness of pubescence, postpubescence and
prepubescence.[7]
